{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616517"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:04:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16395"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16395"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.18,0.46,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9086"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116518"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9086"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98510"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7114"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21589"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116518"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebral hemispheres have distinct functional specialisations. Most people have a dominant hemisphere (usually left) and a non-dominant hemisphere (usually right).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cognitive functions is most likely to be processed primarily in the non-dominant cerebral hemisphere?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mathematical problem solving","Language comprehension","Spatial awareness","Sequential processing","Logical reasoning"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe non-dominant hemisphere (typically the right hemisphere in right-handed individuals) is specialised for visuospatial processing and holistic perception. \u003Cstrong\u003ESpatial awareness\u003C/strong\u003E is therefore primarily processed in the non-dominant hemisphere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMathematical problem solving\u003C/strong\u003E requires analytical and sequential processing, which are key functions of the dominant hemisphere. \u003Cstrong\u003ELanguage comprehension\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in Wernicke\u0027s area within the dominant hemisphere. \u003Cstrong\u003ESequential processing\u003C/strong\u003E is a fundamental characteristic of dominant hemisphere function, involving the ability to process information in a step-by-step manner. \u003Cstrong\u003ELogical reasoning\u003C/strong\u003E involves analytical thinking and structured analysis, both of which are predominantly handled by the dominant hemisphere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe non-dominant hemisphere is also responsible for facial recognition, emotional interpretation, and processing of musical elements such as melody and pitch. Understanding hemispheric specialisation is crucial for localising neurological deficits and understanding stroke syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The non-dominant (usually right) hemisphere specialises in visuospatial processing, emotional interpretation, and holistic perception.","The dominant (usually left) hemisphere specialises in language, sequential processing, and analytical tasks.","Hemispheric specialisation helps explain patterns of deficits seen in stroke and other focal neurological conditions."],"references":["de Oliveira FF, Correia Marin Sde M, Ferreira Bertolucci PH. Communicating with the non-dominant hemisphere: Implications for neurological rehabilitation. Neural Regen Res. 2013 May 5;8(13):1236-46. doi: 10.3969/j.issn.1673-5374.2013.13.009. PMID: 25206418; PMCID: PMC4107603.","Corballis MC. Left brain, right brain: facts and fantasies. PLoS Biol. 2014 Jan;12(1):e1001767. doi: 10.1371/journal.pbio.1001767. Epub 2014 Jan 21. PMID: 24465175; PMCID: PMC3897366.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98510"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16395"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98510"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9086"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116518"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving in